<br>
I am writing this now as a summary of a few of my main points, the basic errors made when creating EQ, or in running it these past 4 years.<br>
<br>
I won't suggest that I haven't enjoyed EQ or that I don't think for the most part it has been very well designed, but for future products of this type if for no other reason, I present my top XX list of things that were or are mistakes.<br>
<br>
1) The con system, unfortunately for VI they choose way back when not to have a con system that was equivalent for PC's and NPC's, in other words a level 1 mob != level 1 PC, and a level 50 mob != level 50 PC for relative power. <br>
<br>
This has had many effects that continue to trouble the basic design of the game, the single most significant of these is the relational scaled power of certain types of spells. Charms/Mezs/Roots etc... any spell which renders a mob incapable of acting directly or reduces there effectiveness by a set amount(ex. slow) scales exponentially with character level, which is why in expansions like various and luclin you saw the role of enchanter vs. main target mob reduced for powerful targets.<br>
<br>
Now obviously this goes double for any spell, which turns the mobs considerable power against it, ie. charm, I won't bother going into graphs or direct numeric examinations of just how out of whack this has all become those numbers only ever become debating points.<br>
<br>
The effect that equal relative power would have had is simple, if a target mob is level 60 and a pc is level 60, then a spell which directly eliminates the ability of a mob of equal level to act is understandable and certainly balanced with those taking and doing damage.<br>
<br>
This has also had the effect of making soloing vs. grouping vs. raiding a major balancing act, if a 60 PC warrior is approx equal to a 60 mob warrior(either would win 50% of the time solo with reasonably skilled people) then<br>
<br>
If a mob is meant to be a &quot;raid level target&quot; then simply raises its level, does it really matter if a target is red by 10 levels or red by 40? so long as everyone can effect it.<br>
<br>
This leads me directly into point number<br>
<br>
2) The level factor, direct level as a factor in the game mechanics is used WAY to much in EQ, direct level should have a small effect on most things, whether it is attack ability, save ability...<br>
<br>
For some strange reason the game designers decided early on that level would be some kind of overriding statistic meaning literally 10x as much as any other statistic.<br>
<br>
This has had the effect of separating people based upon level to such an extent that OFTEN the people with whom you most enjoy associating you are unable to because of level difference. Having literally a 6-10 level range that you can associate with for the majority of the game means. This has also marginalized the value of skill vs. level and gear. In EQ gear and level are king, in my best guess making up 90% of a characters overall value, what skill exists is primarily a function of how good your computer and connection are.<br>
<br>
The effect that reducing the value of level in most of the calculations in EQ would have is to in effect increase the value of gear and skill, something that would allow for more specialized characters threw equipment selection and the application of tactical methods. In addition if level value was reduced then the level spread could easily be justified to have been increased allowing players more grouping options.<br>
<br>
3) exp value determination system, part of the con system really, the problem here is that a level 50 mob solo can total certain level 60 people, while getting totaled by other people in turn, in addition to the fact that equipment plays such a HUGE role in determining what is difficult and what is not for any particular class or level.<br>
<br>
The solution is rather simple really, a relative con system in combination with a falling mob xp value. When you consider the nature of the theory behind &quot;xp&quot; both are perfectly reasonable, even obvious and logical (always an added bonus) The con system would probably be the easiest and could tie in nicely with a relative value system determined by system economics. <br>
<br>
In other words Base Level + relative value of equipment * class situation modifier(cleric soloing 5, cleric grouping 2 etc... which could of course become an easily determined sliding value based upon xp garnered by classes per time period average), the falling mob xp value is simple, the more times you kill a mob(type of mob) the lower that mobs xp value falls, this is in line with both the &quot;anti-camping&quot; policy and the theory that your not going to learn much from killed a goblin for the 10000th time as you did for your first 1000 (where do they keep coming from btw).<br>
<br>
This would have the effect of making the game more &quot;realistic&quot; within its own boundaries and philosophies of the genre, and creating a circumstance where the relative &quot;power&quot; of a character is much more accurately gauged in comparison to the mobs there fighting.<br>
<br>
4) Gear, while I realize that the mainstay of the issue involved here (here being in EQ) is the dated engine, and in all fairness this complaint can't truly be made before SoL, I will state it as a MAJOR issue in the game, there are a number of &quot;sub-problems&quot; here, the first being the general statistical nature of the value of gear. <br>
<br>
In general an upgrade to a piece of equipment will have upgraded ac/hp/mana/attributes/saves. And while for certain pieces of equipment this is fine, There are FAR to few items with &quot;unique and interesting&quot; effects. Even now in EQ there are very few to no items that are truly interesting, there are items that make people drool to be sure but nothing that creates a new dynamic, nothing that lets people truly break out of the base tactical molds.<br>
<br>
New and interesting items would create a sense of value that isn't based directly upon statistics, consider the focus items and there value next to a piece of loot, I personally removed a vulak earring to wear my focus earring, the statistics on the vulak earring were FAR superior to focus earring, but the earring had an effect that outweighed any ear slot item in the game and yet was both reasonable and balanced. Interesting items can be both balanced and invaluable, quite the benefit when your trying to keep a game from becoming stagnant.<br>
<br>
As another &quot;sub-issue&quot; related to gear, the sheer volume of it comes to mind, why is it that every MA of every major guild uses the same 2 weapons and the best weapons at that? would it really be that difficult to have even 10x as many unique items of relatively similar value? This really not that difficult, lets for example take a BF(blood frenzy), generally acknowledged to be the best SoL available taunt weapon (ignore for a moment that it comes off a mob that can be done with 20 people-and no I @#%$ you not), what would it hurt if one of them was a 16/21 weapon that gave 150hp, or had a slightly different effect... adding 100 more lines of hate etc...<br>
<br>
Named loot should be FAR less common then it is, at this point I don't think I know of a major warrior on my server that doesn't have BF (still the best taunt weapon available imho) and there all exactly the same. This could all be handled very easily by even the most basic of randomizing modifiers.<br>
<br>
Less loot would only increase the value of individual pieces of loot and in conjunction with loot that is at least to some extent randomized and more interesting with more unique abilities could create an environment where loot is more or less then the sum of its statistics, imagine an environment where loot was not so easy to rank...<br>
<br>
No-Drop/level requirements... etc... is another area of loot that I have some trouble with, philosophically I have a real problem with twinkling in an RPG, having said that, at this point I don't consider EQ to be an RPG it is a hierarchal strategy game which has a high minimum entry fee in time. I don't really in any sense have a problem with a high level person giving a item of some value to a low level person simply because in any kind of practical social situation that WOULD happen having said that twinking for the purposes of power leveling has always struck me as rather lame (not that I didn't do it once or twice or 9 times) So for no particular reason I would like to see the following done<br>
<br>
1 character per server per account (if you want to play another character then start on another server, its not that tough)<br>
<br>
Remove all no drop items from the game with the exception of perhaps some &quot;soul bound&quot; items that return to you every time you zone, or maybe do damage to someone else trying to use them, but this would be an item hook rather then punitive game mechanic.<br>
<br>
remove level required and recommended from items with the exception of perhaps some &quot;intelligent&quot; items that simply will not allow themselves to be used by &quot;lesser powers&quot; but this ONLY if named items are made FAR rarer.<br>
<br>
I think that would create a situation where twinking with significant items would only occur very rarely but no more rarely then would be practical or realistic in a social game.<br>
<br>
And the last thing I will talk about is the “realism” of loot, while receiving a sword from a relatively humanoid mob is fine by me, receiving one from a giant worm is well, silly. The simple solution to this is to involve the tradeskill people in this, what if and enchanter + blacksmith could combine there talents to make a bitching hat out of some body part, maybe make a half dozen of them… at least it wouldn’t seem quite so silly to be looking at someone holding a dagger that’s supposed to be some creatures spine and actually looks like a masterwork elven dagger.<br>
<br>
<br>
I had some other gear related ones but those are the major ones.<br>
<br>
5) spelldat being client side, this was quite possibly the biggest mistake VI made when originally creating EQ, a parse able file describing the effects of every spell in the game? and what’s worse every &quot;effect&quot; in the game? short and simple never ever ever do this again. being able to match up every aoe, every proc to its exact stats with a parser sucks.<br>
<br>
6) rooted/dting/summoning mobs, these are three of the lamest game effects that exist. <br>
<br>
I will start with rooted mobs, for some strange reason IV will just stand there regardless of how much one of our guilds enchanters pisses him off, I don't quite know why, I know that he sees him and is annoyed at him, but he just stands there. This might be a cool effect for ONE mob, having more then one mob rooted those is just plain silly. Off the top of my head, perhaps, a mob shackled to the floor with some chains, perhaps a mob confined to a room with some sort of magical barrier , perhaps some mob confined to his own tiny little dimension ok ok ok. But a mob that just stands there unmoving is idiotic on virtually every level that exists, it doesn’t even serve game mechanics in any real meaningful way.<br>
<br>
Dting mobs, I am sorry but this is just plane annoying, the actual game effect is moderate depending on how often a mob does this but all this does is increase zerg factor, there is no skill in getting or not getting DT’d, instant death maybe realistic under some circumstances it may suit the enviorment, but to the vast majority of players something that is inevitable despite skill gear levels or anything else is just plane annoying. It adds nothing to the game of value and takes away a great deal of fun, but that’s just my opinion.<br>
<br>
Summoning, what I would like to know is who thought this up? I mean seriously, what inbred jed thought it would be a good idea if mobs of no particular importance or relevance could just wave there hands and bring characters into melee range. While I understand this was to cover up any potential shoddy programming in its many forms wouldn’t it have been better to create 2 simple situations to cover this up? Ranged attacks and fleeing? If a mob can’t reach someone he starts using his ranged attack, if he doesn’t have one or if the pc is out of range the mob flees? maybe calling a friend with a ranged attack if there intelligent enough for that?<br>
<br>
I don’t know I understand the source of all three of these things but in practice and in game they are imo the worst combat design flaws I have ever seen in any game bar none (whether in EQ or any other game).<br>
<br>
7) The damage problem, due to the fact that there are far to few actual roles in EQ and far to many classes there is a large lump of classes whose “sole” purpose is damage (while no class actually doesn’t have any other skills these all claim to have none) These include Wizards(who have teleports skins blah blah), mages(who have focus items, mod rods blah blah), rogues (who have the only virtually full invis), beastlords (who have SLOW, and some excellent buffs), monks (who have FD and mend), necro’s (who have umm lots). All these classes veying for one roll(and theres more then that really) and whats worse is that there are classes that aren’t even as valuable as these in most circumstances because they don’t do a lot of damage. So the problem comes done to the fact that EQ comes down to A) absorbing damage and B) doing damage, the solution is rather simple, well really theres a few potential different solutions. You can either add a C) and a D) to EQ or you could balance the actual game but balancing classes ability to do the A) and B), that means taking into account just how much a 70% slow does vs. how much a cleric can heal and how much damage a rogue can do. Personally I would prefer a combination of both, I think that classes should be reletivly balanced in A) and B) while adding a C) and D) of whatever type can only add depth to what is largely a very shallow world.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START 8) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/glasses.gif ALT="8)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  economics, its odd that a world that is to large for so many reasons can be to small for economics. Unfortunatly its true that virtually no normal economic rules work on a population of 1000 people (the approximate active in economics on each server). So how do you change this? Pretty simple again, make a mega bazaar where people from EVERY server can interact, if for no other reason then an arena fight between FOH and AL would just be to entertaining it would have the minor side effect of correcting about 75% of EQ’s current economic troubles. The problem with the formation of EQ’s economy is that it was designed and based upon a much larger scale economy then actually exisits.<br>
<br>
I understand that perhaps this would be “technically unfeasible” but I really honestly can’t think of any direct barriers considering all of EQ is done by “zone” farms not “per server” farms.<br>
<br>
one other things about the economics, make the npcs buy goods at a half assed reasonable price, after all goods leaving the game is only a good thing in a game where nothing wears out.<br>
<br>
Hmmm theres more but looks like I actually have some work to do for a bit  woot…<br>
