<br>
3. The XP system.-- I personally like the idea of a Threat rating on an NPC rather than level determining the reward for defeating it.<br>
Lets say we have 2 mobs, both level 5 with 150hps, hits for 21 max, with an AC of say 100.  The first is an Orc centurion, the second the Orc Apprentice.  Currently, both will grant 50 xp when killed since they are level 5, but that's not really fair, because the apprentice will sit there and chaincast Blindness on you all frigging day until it's killed.  In a system with a threat rating, the Apprentice would be worth more xp despite it's level, because spellcasting would raise the difficulty of the encounter, unless it was balanced by some other factor, like low hp, less attk or damage, etc.  If the AI is going to be so stupid as to have casters beating on PC's with (with warrior like ac/hp/damage) and casting spells once in a while as well, then they need to be worth more, or drop more loot, or some other balancing factor.<br>
<br>
4. The Gear issue.-- Here is where we part way somewhat.<br>
The problem with gear and it's distribution is the same problem with 90% of the game's design: Lack of Imagination.  Personally, I would like to see tradeskills see a much larger role in gear than we currently do, combined with item decay.<br>
<br>
Problem 1-- With item decay, we quickly run into the problem of naked people walking around, because even orc pawns are kind of stingy with their cloth armor, much less anything actually substancial dropping.  Solution--standard gear is extremely common, like something on EVERY mob.  If it looks like it's wearing leather armor, then by god you should be able to loot it, if you can stand the smell of an orc pawn's skivvy's, of course.  This creates a problem of it's own--if you consider newbies dressed in leather or even basic chain a problem, but even that is easily addressed.<br>
<br>
Quality vs. Quantity<br>
Make the everymob common armor very poor in stats--after all, orcs don't look to be very patient, skilled, or all that maintenence minded either. In fact, respectable merchants won't touch the stuff--so you can't sell it for an easy fortune.  However, with a bit of skill, you could perhaps salvage the leather from the armor, and with several pieces make a better piece of your own armor from it.  Of course, killing animals and getting their pelts would be cleaner and easier, but they would have to first survive an extra tradeskill check to be made appropriate for use in armor--with the various qualities determining exactly how good the armor can be made, for instance, only very high quality leather could be used in the creation of the legendary elven cloaks that conceal the wearer from their enemies (+% to Hide and modifies racial ability to do so).  So a newbie takes a wolf hide, and has his choice of attempting to cure it into low quality leather, or high quality leather, and the quality of the armor made from it would be likewise modified.  The salvaged orc leather would only be of the lowest quality--and thus nearly useless, reflecting it's common status.<br>
<br>
As we go higher in level, the same principals can be applied.  If the monster involved is roughly humanoid, you could probably wear it's chain, or even plate armors, but not without some refitting.  Orcs are bigger than elves, smaller than barbarians, etc.  For that chain to be useful, your going to have to use an armor skill to see if it can be salvaged, and even so, taken as is be very poor.  Some races might actually have very high quality armor available, but have any of you seen a Shissar?  Care to try and wear his pants?  In these cases, the loot serves as raw materials for making of the items, rather than as direct loot.   This is very important because of Item decay.<br>
<br>
Decay, Ordinary stuff, and the exceptional.<br>
Without decay, the above seems like monty haul, and the world will soon be awash in player created armors salvaged from the various creatures of norrath.  With decay, your going to be needing more of whatever to replace or repair what your wearing.  With cloth and leather, this is an easy, trivial matter. <br>
<br>
However, we must speak of the decay and repair of more expensive items.  You could, with all of your salvaging, simply sell your salvaged goods, and pay an armorer (NPC or PC) to fix it.  This is fine, especially for common items.  If your a skilled tradesman, you could take your raw matierials, and fix it yourself--also fine, and greatly depends on your level of skill vs the quality of the item.  Joe Sebelis might know how to maintain an ordinary suit of plate armor, but it takes a fine craftsman indeed to repair the exceptional armors developed by the various races, and near godlike skill to maintain the powerfull enchantments imbued into ancient armors who's secrets of manufacture have been lost for ages, like those found in the dank dungeons of ancient creatures that should have died long ago.   Some items might require very skilled PC repairman, as no NPC's are going to have the skill required, or if they do, the cost is likely to be outrageous.<br>
<br>
The Point.<br>
What's the point of all this?  I'd personally like to see elves wearing elven chain.  High leveled/Rich elves would wear high quality chain, low leveled/unskilled elves would wear what they can get.  Same goes with all the races.  I'd like to have to make a choice, salvaging the magic cloth of Venril Sathir's robe to maintain and repair the known enchantments of my own people, or else suffering the maintenence of the ancient and powerful enchantments that are no longer fully understood, or perhaps were never understood.  Perhaps some items would be special in that they do not need this maintenence, but that would be a rare and wonderful power of it's own.  Currently, few wear cultural armors as most are matched or exceeded easily by dropped items.  Also, while I may not be able to kill Venril, or Vindi, or Emp...  I might aspire to salvage enough high quality enchanted materials from his underlings to make good items for myself given time---Thus the casual player isn't shut out, he's just got to go down a different path.<br>
<br>
5. The Spelldat file being client side.--  I'm half and half with you on this.<br>
No, we should not know exactly what every mob in the game can do to us--unless we directly experiance it, and perhaps not even then.  However, If I'm a Wizard, I should know <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Exactly</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> what the spell I'm casting does, if it's in my book, I had to learn it.  This should have been handled in game however, Damage, duration, range, special effects, etc... should all be listed when I rightclick the spell for a description.  I'd be terrified IRL if the pilot of my airplane just worked the knobs of the aircraft controls without knowing what they did.  I'd be astounded if the carpenters that built my house had no clue other than the name of the item what a hammer was for.  Now, if the spell came from an item, like a right click, then yes, perhaps that spell--as it cannot be permanantly learned-- would have it's details being a bit foggy.<br>
<br>
6. Lame effects.-- I agree to a point.<br>
To me, the only lame effects are the ones that make absolutly no sense.  Summoning- unless the mob is a caster, or drops an item with Right click Call of the Hero, it should not summon without a very good reason.  Perhaps summoning is a special ability of the funny race of moon men, or dragons developed it eons ago, etc...   But ever other Giant, Toad, Wurm, High levelmob x should not be able to summon you.   <br>
I agree with Death Touch on the grounds of gameplay.  Now that is truely lame, to just kill someone.  It should, at the very least, get a resist.  Unless it's used sparingly-- IE mob x will deathtouch x times every 4 minutes--meaning you have 4 min to kill the mob or half your force is gone, in 8 min, your likely wiped... its just stupid.<br>
Rooted mobs make no sense, unless there is story to back it.  Perhaps the mob has been commanded to guard this spot, and won't move from it regardless of the consequenses...  But to root it just to prevent a certain pulling technique is stupid.  It's another indication of the lack of imagination at VI.<br>
<br>
7.  Economy.  It is what it is.  Making it serverwide would not be better, nor neccesarily worse, just different.  Most people will still generally charge the maximum amount they can get for any given item.  Item quality and risk/reward  will still be out of balance from Original/Kunark/Vellious/Luclin/PoP because VI has no imagination, and is unwilling to give us a way to improve old items (with very few and unreasonably high cost exceptions). <p><br>
